---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'SafetyWing in France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-warning', text: 'Visa Compliance Warning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'coverage-types', text: 'Coverage Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pricing', text: 'Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'using-in-france', text: 'Using SafetyWing in France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'puma-transition', text: 'PUMA Transition', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-its-for', text: 'Who Should Choose SafetyWing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Health Insurance in France', href: '/countries/france/insurance' },
  { title: 'SafetyWing Review', href: '/providers/safetywing' },
  { title: 'SafetyWing vs Cigna', href: '/compare/safetywing-vs-cigna-global' },
];

const coverageColumns = [
  { key: 'benefit', header: 'Benefit' },
  { key: 'nomad', header: 'Nomad Insurance' },
  { key: 'remote', header: 'Remote Health' },
];

const coverageRows = [
  { benefit: 'Type', nomad: 'Travel Medical', remote: 'Health Insurance' },
  { benefit: 'Maximum Coverage', nomad: '$250,000', remote: '$1M-$10M' },
  { benefit: 'Outpatient', nomad: 'Emergency only', remote: 'Full coverage' },
  { benefit: 'Routine Care', nomad: 'Not covered', remote: 'Covered' },
  { benefit: 'Mental Health', nomad: 'Not covered', remote: 'Included' },
  { benefit: 'Pre-existing', nomad: 'Not covered', remote: 'After waiting period' },
  { benefit: 'Visa Compliant', nomad: 'Unlikely', remote: 'Possibly' },
  { benefit: 'Commitment', nomad: 'None', remote: 'Monthly' },
];

const pricingColumns = [
  { key: 'age', header: 'Age' },
  { key: 'nomad', header: 'Nomad Insurance' },
  { key: 'remote', header: 'Remote Health' },
];

const pricingRows = [
  { age: '25-39', nomad: '$45/4 weeks (~€41/mo)', remote: '€90-180/mo' },
  { age: '40-49', nomad: '$76/4 weeks (~€70/mo)', remote: '€140-270/mo' },
  { age: '50-59', nomad: '$117/4 weeks (~€107/mo)', remote: '€230-410/mo' },
  { age: '60-69', nomad: '$189/4 weeks (~€173/mo)', remote: '€370-640/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="SafetyWing Insurance in France"
  description="Guide to using SafetyWing in France. Affordable nomad coverage but may not meet visa requirements. Coverage details and who it's right for."
  headline="SafetyWing Insurance in France"
  subheadline="The digital nomad favorite. Affordable and flexible—but understand France's visa requirements before choosing."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/france-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get a SafetyWing Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/safetywing"
>
  <h2 id="overview">SafetyWing in France</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing is popular with digital nomads, and France—especially Paris, Lyon, and the Riviera—attracts remote workers from around the world. But France has specific visa requirements, and SafetyWing Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance, not the comprehensive health insurance French consulates typically require.
  </p>
  <p>
    For tourists on 90-day Schengen visits or digital nomads doing short stays, SafetyWing can provide affordable emergency coverage. For those applying for French long-stay visas, you'll likely need a more comprehensive policy.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€41</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Per month (Nomad, age 30)</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">180+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Countries covered</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">0</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Commitment required</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-warning">Visa Compliance Warning</h2>

  <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-red-900 mb-2">Important: SafetyWing May Not Meet French Visa Requirements</h3>
    <p class="text-red-800">
      <strong>SafetyWing Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance, not comprehensive health insurance.</strong> French consulates require health insurance covering at least €30,000 with hospitalization, emergency care, and repatriation. While Nomad Insurance includes these elements, consulates may reject travel medical insurance as it doesn't cover routine care. Verify with your specific consulate before applying.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>French Visa Insurance Requirements</h3>
  <p>
    The VLS-TS Visiteur visa (France's main non-working visa) requires:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Minimum €30,000 medical coverage</li>
    <li>Hospitalization and emergency care</li>
    <li>Medical evacuation and repatriation</li>
    <li>Valid for entire intended stay</li>
    <li>Typically: comprehensive health insurance, not travel medical</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Where SafetyWing Can Work</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Schengen tourist visa (90 days):</strong> May be accepted for short stays</li>
    <li><strong>Digital nomad short stays:</strong> Coverage while exploring France</li>
    <li><strong>Supplemental travel coverage:</strong> Alongside PUMA for trips abroad</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Where SafetyWing Likely Won't Work</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>VLS-TS Visiteur visa:</strong> Consulates typically require comprehensive health insurance</li>
    <li><strong>Student visa (VLS-TS Étudiant):</strong> Usually requires specific student coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Long-stay visa applications:</strong> Travel medical insurance often rejected</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">For Visa-Compliant Insurance</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      If you need insurance for a French long-stay visa, consider comprehensive options like <strong>Cigna Global</strong>, <strong>Allianz Care</strong>, <strong>AXA Global</strong>, or <strong>BUPA Global</strong>. These are recognized health insurers that meet French visa requirements. Remote Health may also work—verify with your consulate.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="coverage-types">Coverage Options</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing offers two very different products:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={coverageColumns} rows={coverageRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Nomad Insurance (Travel Medical)</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing's famous product—subscription-based travel medical insurance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Emergency medical treatment</li>
    <li>Acute illness that arises while traveling</li>
    <li>Accidents and injuries</li>
    <li>Emergency dental (pain relief only, up to $1,000)</li>
    <li>Medical evacuation up to $100,000</li>
    <li>Lost baggage, travel delays</li>
    <li>Limited US coverage (15 days per 90-day period)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What Nomad Insurance Doesn't Cover</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Routine doctor visits</li>
    <li>Ongoing prescriptions</li>
    <li>Pre-existing conditions</li>
    <li>Mental health</li>
    <li>Maternity</li>
    <li>Dental (except emergency)</li>
    <li>Preventive care</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Remote Health (Full Health Insurance)</h3>
  <p>
    Remote Health is comprehensive health insurance—completely different from Nomad Insurance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Coverage up to $10 million</li>
    <li>Full outpatient care</li>
    <li>Mental health included</li>
    <li>Maternity available (12-month wait)</li>
    <li>Pre-existing conditions (24-month wait)</li>
    <li>More likely to meet visa requirements—verify first</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Understand What You're Buying"
    description="Nomad Insurance is travel medical, not comprehensive health insurance."
    buttonText="Learn More"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing's pricing is simple and transparent:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={pricingColumns} rows={pricingRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Nomad Insurance Pricing</h3>
  <p>
    Billed every 4 weeks with no commitment:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Age-based pricing only</li>
    <li>$250 deductible per incident</li>
    <li>One child under 10 free per adult</li>
    <li>Cancel anytime—no penalties</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Remote Health Pricing</h3>
  <p>
    Monthly billing with more variables:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Age affects pricing significantly</li>
    <li>Deductible options: $0-$5,000</li>
    <li>Coverage area affects price</li>
    <li>Higher premiums but comprehensive coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="using-in-france">Using SafetyWing in France</h2>

  <h3>Finding Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing doesn't have a traditional provider network. Use any licensed provider in France:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Private hospitals (Hôpital Américain, cliniques privées)</li>
    <li>Private clinics</li>
    <li>English-speaking doctors (common in Paris, Nice)</li>
    <li>Urgent care centers (SOS Médecins)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Claims Process</h3>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2">
    <li>Pay the French provider upfront</li>
    <li>Get itemized receipt (facture détaillée)</li>
    <li>Submit claim via SafetyWing portal</li>
    <li>Wait 10-30 days for reimbursement</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Direct billing is limited. Expect to pay and file for reimbursement.
  </p>

  <h3>French Healthcare Costs</h3>
  <p>
    French healthcare is reasonably priced for routine care:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>GP visit: €25-50</li>
    <li>Specialist: €50-150</li>
    <li>Lab work: €30-80</li>
    <li>Urgent care (SOS Médecins): €50-100</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    You can pay for routine care out of pocket and use SafetyWing for emergencies—if you're not applying for a long-stay visa.
  </p>

  <h2 id="puma-transition">PUMA Transition</h2>
  <p>
    France's PUMA (Protection Universelle Maladie) provides excellent public healthcare after 3+ months of legal residency.
  </p>

  <h3>The Timeline</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Months 1-3:</strong> Private insurance required (no PUMA eligibility)</li>
    <li><strong>Month 3:</strong> Apply for PUMA enrollment</li>
    <li><strong>Months 3-9:</strong> Wait for PUMA processing</li>
    <li><strong>Month 6-9:</strong> Receive Carte Vitale</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>If You Qualified for a Visa with SafetyWing</h3>
  <p>
    If your consulate accepted SafetyWing (unlikely but possible for some visa types), you'd continue it during the 6-9 month PUMA wait, then transition to PUMA + mutuelle.
  </p>

  <h3>After PUMA Enrollment</h3>
  <p>
    Once enrolled in PUMA, most expats use:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>PUMA:</strong> Covers ~70% of medical costs</li>
    <li><strong>Mutuelle:</strong> €30-150/month top-up for the remaining ~30%</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    SafetyWing could supplement PUMA for travel outside France, but dedicated travel insurance is typically cheaper.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Should Choose SafetyWing</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Nomad Insurance Good For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>Tourists on 90-day Schengen visits</li>
        <li>Digital nomads doing short stays</li>
        <li>Young, healthy travelers</li>
        <li>Budget-conscious nomads</li>
        <li>Those testing France before committing</li>
        <li>Supplemental travel coverage (with PUMA)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Remote Health May Work For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
        <li>Those wanting comprehensive coverage</li>
        <li>Mental health needs</li>
        <li>Some visa applications (verify first)</li>
        <li>Pre-PUMA transition period</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Consider Alternatives If:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Applying for VLS-TS Visiteur visa</strong> — Need comprehensive health insurance</li>
    <li><strong>Applying for any French long-stay visa</strong> — Travel medical typically not accepted</li>
    <li><strong>You have pre-existing conditions</strong> — Nomad Insurance excludes them</li>
    <li><strong>You're over 50</strong> — Consider more comprehensive coverage</li>
    <li><strong>You need routine care</strong> — Nomad Insurance doesn't cover it</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Right Choice for You?"
    description="Make sure you choose insurance that meets France's requirements."
    buttonText="Compare All France Options"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
  />

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can I use SafetyWing for a French long-stay visa?</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Unlikely.</strong> French consulates typically require comprehensive health insurance, not travel medical insurance. SafetyWing Nomad Insurance may be rejected. Verify with your specific consulate before applying. Remote Health may be more likely to be accepted—verify first.
  </p>

  <h3>Is SafetyWing enough for a 90-day Schengen visit?</h3>
  <p>
    For tourism, Nomad Insurance provides emergency coverage. Schengen visa requirements for insurance are less strict than long-stay visas. Check your specific visa requirements—some Schengen visas require comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>What's the difference between Nomad Insurance and Remote Health?</h3>
  <p>
    Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance—emergency coverage only. Remote Health is actual health insurance with comprehensive coverage including routine care, mental health, and maternity. Remote Health costs more but is more likely to meet visa requirements.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I switch from SafetyWing to PUMA + mutuelle?</h3>
  <p>
    If you're in France on a valid long-stay visa, you can apply for PUMA after 3 months. PUMA eligibility doesn't depend on your current insurance. However, if SafetyWing wasn't accepted for your visa application, this scenario wouldn't apply.
  </p>

  <h3>Does SafetyWing cover French hospitals?</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing covers any licensed provider. You'll pay upfront and claim reimbursement. There's no direct billing arrangement with French hospitals.
  </p>

  <h3>Is SafetyWing good for digital nomads in France?</h3>
  <p>
    For short stays without visa requirements, yes—it's affordable emergency coverage. For longer stays requiring visas, you'll likely need comprehensive health insurance instead.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Understand Your Options"
    description="Choose insurance that meets France's specific requirements."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. SafetyWing Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance, not comprehensive health insurance. French visa requirements vary by consulate. Always verify insurance requirements with your specific French consulate before visa applications.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
